Package org.ivoa.dm.stc.coords

Class TimeFrame

java.lang.Object
org.ivoa.dm.stc.coords.CoordFrame
org.ivoa.dm.stc.coords.TimeFrame
All Implemented Interfaces:
org.ivoa.vodml.jaxb.XmlIdManagement, org.ivoa.vodml.jpa.JPAManipulations, org.ivoa.vodml.jpa.JPAManipulationsForObjectType<Long>
@Entity @VoDml(id="coords:TimeFrame", role=objectType) public class TimeFrame extends CoordFrame implements org.ivoa.vodml.jpa.JPAManipulationsForObjectType<Long>, org.ivoa.vodml.jaxb.XmlIdManagement
A TimeFrame SHALL include a time scale and reference position. It MAY also include a reference direction. objectType: TimeFrame

  • Field Details

    • refPosition

      @VoDml(id="coords:TimeFrame.refPosition", role=attribute, type="coords:RefLocation", typeRole=dataType) protected RefLocation refPosition
      The spatial location at which the coordinate is considered to have been taken. This model supports locations provided as either a standard reference position (e.g. GEOCENTER), or a coordinate specifying a custom location (e.g. long, lat, height). : Attribute refPosition : multiplicity 1

    • timescale

      @VoDml(id="coords:TimeFrame.timescale", role=attribute, type="ivoa:string", typeRole=primitiveType) protected String timescale
      The time scale sets the reference frame. The value MUST be selected from the controlled vocabulary at the given URL. : Attribute timescale : multiplicity 1

    • refDirection

      @VoDml(id="coords:TimeFrame.refDirection", role=attribute, type="coords:RefLocation", typeRole=dataType) protected RefLocation refDirection
      The reference direction is needed if the time stamps are transformed to a time frame with a different reference position. In those situations, the solar system ephemeris also comes into play. See: FITS WCS Paper IV for details, but in short: The reference direction, presumably the direction to the thing being observed, is used in conjunction with the reference position and planetary ephemeris to determine the correction applied for the path length change. To be fully useful, one also needs to know the location at which the observation was made ( i.e. the observatory location), which is not considered to be Frame metadata. : Attribute refDirection : multiplicity 0..1

    • TimeFrame

      public TimeFrame(RefLocation refPosition, String timescale, RefLocation refDirection)
      full parameter constructor.
      Parameters:
      refPosition - The spatial location at which the coordinate is considered to have been taken. This model supports locations provided as either a standard reference position (e.g. GEOCENTER), or a coordinate specifying a custom location (e.g. long, lat, height).
      timescale - The time scale sets the reference frame. The value MUST be selected from the controlled vocabulary at the given URL.
      refDirection - The reference direction is needed if the time stamps are transformed to a time frame with a different reference position. In those situations, the solar system ephemeris also comes into play. See: FITS WCS Paper IV for details, but in short: The reference direction, presumably the direction to the thing being observed, is used in conjunction with the reference position and planetary ephemeris to determine the correction applied for the path length change. To be fully useful, one also needs to know the location at which the observation was made ( i.e. the observatory location), which is not considered to be Frame metadata.
